    {
      "datasource": {
        "type": "prometheus",
        "uid": "cfpijjnoxf9q8d"
      },
      "description": " vllm:e2e_request_latency_seconds is the outcome, but vllm:request_queue_time_seconds, vllm:request_prefill_time_seconds, and vllm:request_decode_time_seconds are the causes. If P95 e2e latency blows up, you want to look at these three side by side to see which phase is growing — that answers \"is it slow, and where?\" directly:\n\nQueue time growing → you're saturated, requests are waiting for a slot (scheduler-bound)\nPrefill time growing → long input prompts are expensive to process (compute-bound on input)\nDecode time growing → generation itself is slow, or you've got too many concurrent decodes competing for GPU (compute-bound on output, or KV-cache-bound)",
